Use Tom Keelin's Metalog functions (https://www.metalogdistributions.com/) to create a random walk forecast for the next month. These do a much better job of capturing the heteroskedasticity in financial variables than the usual normal or t-distributions. Then did a simple linear opinion pool (LOP) with the crowd. The result is a little less extreme than the Metalog alone but should be a reasonable way to push out forecasts to the target end date.

The S&P only broke through the 3,800 barrier in Jan 2021 during peak covid. With a war, a fuel crisis, a debt-fuelled financial implosion and monetary tightening, I can't see it going up too much over the next couple of months. It took 5 years to recover from the 2007 financial crisis (from above 1500 in 2007 to above 1500 in 2012). We can eliminate the chance of it being over 4700 as it would need to achieve a new record during a recession. It also seems to hit a support level at 4100, and regularly bounces to 4400. There's a strong chance it'll be in the 4100 to 4400 range, but as the support level is dropping by around 100 points a month there's a bigger downside risk than upside.

I have used the normal distribution to analyze existing data (very rudimentary, but I consider it more reliable than many economic analysis or gut feeling). I have used historical data since 1990, calculated that the variation in periods of six months has an average of 4.7% and a standard deviation of 10.54ppt. Therefore, the expected growth for the next six months is the value of Dec 31st x 1.0477 We consider that we have no better information to predict, as the current price reflects all available information (efficient market hypothesis). Finally, we have used normal distribution (4.7, 10.54) to assign probabilities to each intervals. I would be happy to hear about different approaches, and/or possible mistakes in the calcualtions.
